2015-06-09 10:10:04	-->	darrencauthon (~darrencau@99.42.238.241) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 10:10:28	cpuguy83	IanVorn: How would you do it without the container?
2015-06-09 10:11:04	<--	n1x (~n1x@unaffiliated/n1xnc0d3) has quit (Ping timeout: 252 seconds)
2015-06-09 10:11:15	<--	carl- (~carl_@spacewalkers.comhem.com) has quit (Ping timeout: 256 seconds)
2015-06-09 10:11:19	-->	iamjarvo (~textual@69.241.19.12) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 10:11:27	bkc_	cpuguy83: is 127.1 "linked" to the host?
2015-06-09 10:11:29	IanVorn	I'd like to get the rails app container using the host db, is that possible or not recommended?
2015-06-09 10:11:32	<--	KyleJamesWalker (~kylejames@cpe-75-82-146-138.socal.res.rr.com) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-09 10:11:49	bkc_	I thought the containers had their own lo-if
2015-06-09 10:11:53	cpuguy83	bkc_: No, localhost is local to a net namespace
2015-06-09 10:11:53	-->	bexelbie (bexelbie@fedora/bexelbie) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 10:12:12	bkc_	IanVorn: yes it's possible, it's "recommended"
2015-06-09 10:12:16	-->	KyleJamesWalker (~kylejames@cpe-75-82-146-138.socal.res.rr.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 10:12:19	<--	vikasyaligar (~vikasyali@119.82.127.66) has quit (Ping timeout: 245 seconds)
2015-06-09 10:12:50	bkc_	cpuguy83: then you'd have to open mysql to docker0
2015-06-09 10:12:53	cpuguy83	IanVorn: Your Rails app communicates with the database over a socket of some sort... generally either a unix socket or a TCP socket. It really just comes down to networking.
2015-06-09 10:13:11	cpuguy83	bkc_: Or some other interface, or a unix sock
2015-06-09 10:13:17	cpuguy83	Or use --net=host
2015-06-09 10:13:18	bkc_	fair enough
2015-06-09 10:13:24	--	gchamoul is now known as gchamoul|BRB
2015-06-09 10:13:25	bkc_	--net=host is ugly :P
2015-06-09 10:13:39	cpuguy83	It's not bad depending on what you are doing.
2015-06-09 10:15:03	-->	TheCuban (~thecuban@208.31.255.33) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 10:15:05	IanVorn	do I have to setup the container differently, or run it in a special way?
2015-06-09 10:15:31	IanVorn	plus I'm on mac, so have the added redirection of boot2docker vm!
2015-06-09 10:16:28	<--	KyleJamesWalker (~kylejames@cpe-75-82-146-138.socal.res.rr.com) has quit (Ping timeout: 255 seconds)
2015-06-09 10:16:36	cpuguy83	IanVorn: The container, by default, get's it's own network stack which can communicate outside of the container, especially to other addresses on the host.
2015-06-09 10:17:20	IanVorn	yeah, so the rails app normally connects to localhost (postgres)
2015-06-09 10:17:44	cpuguy83	IanVorn: What I'd do is configure the app to always talk to a specific hostname, like `db`
2015-06-09 10:17:59	IanVorn	yep, I read that, and have that setup
2015-06-09 10:18:13	IanVorn	so then I just need db in my hosts file in the container?
2015-06-09 10:18:30	cpuguy83	IanVorn: When you containerize your DB, you can just use `--link` and that will just work. For your current setup, when creating the rails container you'd do `docker run --add-host db:<host ip>`
2015-06-09 10:18:44	-->	gamename (~gamename@c-67-177-166-184.hsd1.tn.comcast.net) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 10:18:53	IanVorn	ah nice, I'll give that a go.
2015-06-09 10:19:02	axl_	IanVorn, dont forget in your database.yml to add the host db
2015-06-09 10:19:12	IanVorn	yeah, got that one done, cheers.
