2015-06-09 13:41:04	@ldlework	d0lph1n98: docker is a daemon, with a client to talk to the daemon. It starts "containers" which are nothing more than isolated unix processes. Containers are created from images, which DockerHub is the distribution system for.
2015-06-09 13:41:11	@ldlework	Everything else works just like normal linux.
2015-06-09 13:41:38	@ldlework	If you have multiple users logging into your Docker host, and using the docker daemon on that host - its as if you had a single user using the daemon on that host.
2015-06-09 13:41:50	<--	adgtl (~anildigit@unaffiliated/anildigital) has quit (Ping timeout: 244 seconds)
2015-06-09 13:41:50	@ldlework	In both cases, starting Docker containers, is exactly like starting -normal unix processes-
2015-06-09 13:42:01	@ldlework	If the users start more containers, they are starting more processes.
2015-06-09 13:42:14	@ldlework	There is no (zero) virtualization
2015-06-09 13:42:48	@ldlework	containers (isolated unix processes) run "locally" using the local kernel. The kernel provides filesystem and networking isolation between the processes so they can't see each other, or the host.
2015-06-09 13:42:51	@ldlework	That's about it.
2015-06-09 13:43:05	-->	nemothekid (~textual@199-241-202-243.PUBLIC.monkeybrains.net) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 13:43:27	-->	kuduk (~kuduk@81.184.233.103.dyn.user.ono.com) has joined #docker
