2015-06-09 13:44:02	d0lph1n98	what about user experience if there are lots of processes running?
2015-06-09 13:44:11	@ldlework	d0lph1n98: literally the same if you were not using Docker at all
2015-06-09 13:44:15	@ldlework	and you had lots of unix processes running
2015-06-09 13:44:19	-->	OrangeTux (~auke@5249F022.cm-4-2d.dynamic.ziggo.nl) has joined #docker
2015-06-09 13:44:24	@ldlework	because Docker containers are -no different- than normal unix processes
2015-06-09 13:44:30	--	Griwes is now known as Serwig
2015-06-09 13:44:39	@ldlework	Docker doesn't make your cpu faster, or your ram have more capacity.
2015-06-09 13:45:13	d0lph1n98	so basically, it depends on the host hardware specification?
2015-06-09 13:45:19	Skuggen	Only if you get the _fast_ editions of the images, but you have to pay for those
2015-06-09 13:45:27	<--	nemothekid (~textual@199-241-202-243.PUBLIC.monkeybrains.net) has quit (Client Quit)
2015-06-09 13:45:39	@ldlework	d0lph1n98: docker has nothing to do with performance
2015-06-09 13:45:59	Skuggen	Well, it's meant to be a faster, more lightweight alternative to full vms
2015-06-09 13:46:00	@ldlework	it doesn't do anything but start processes with some special configuration, so they can't see each other
2015-06-09 13:46:03	@ldlework	that's it!
2015-06-09 13:46:21	@ldlework	Skuggen: its not meant to be "an alternative to VMs"
2015-06-09 13:46:28	@ldlework	That would imply that Docker has the same characteristics of VMs
2015-06-09 13:46:29	@ldlework	It does not.
2015-06-09 13:46:38	@ldlework	It overlaps some use-cases of VMs.
