2015-06-09 15:09:24	marshmn	I'm setting up a Docker environment mainly for development reasons; am I right to think that for dev purposes, the best way is to mount a folder from my local host rather than using a separate 'data container'?
2015-06-09 15:09:37	<--	thebishop (~thebishop@50.243.39.109) has quit (Ping timeout: 250 seconds)
2015-06-09 15:09:53	marshmn	and if so, what's the best way to deal with file ownership/permissions issues?
2015-06-09 15:10:18	<--	nathanleclaire (~nathanlec@c-73-189-234-64.hsd1.ca.comcast.net) has quit (Quit: nathanleclaire)
2015-06-09 15:10:29	<--	seanmcl (~seanmcl@69.64.193.242) has quit (Quit: My MacBook Pro has gone to sleep. ZZZzzz…)
2015-06-09 15:10:30	marshmn	I see lots of advice on the web, which mainly end up saying to use data containers - but I think they are talking about production environments rather than dev ones?
2015-06-09 15:10:48	cpuguy83	marshmn: Correct, for dev I bind-mount my code in.
2015-06-09 15:11:04	vdemeester	marshmn: same here
2015-06-09 15:11:10	marshmn	ok, good
2015-06-09 15:11:13	<--	micah_chatt (~micah_cha@ec2-54-84-43-177.compute-1.amazonaws.com) has quit (Quit: micah_chatt)
2015-06-09 15:11:13	odinnap	same, I usually just mount my local folder when deving
2015-06-09 15:11:40	@ldlework	marshmn: I deal with permissions by not bind-mounting my code in.
2015-06-09 15:11:43	marshmn	do you make your web server run as the same user as your local user or something to manage the file permissions?
2015-06-09 15:11:44	<--	superguenter (~Adium@173-11-90-206-SFBA.hfc.comcastbusiness.net) has quit (Ping timeout: 252 seconds)
2015-06-09 15:11:47	cpuguy83	marshmn: as far perms... can be tricky. Personally since I'm on boot2docker, the dirs uid/gid are remapped to the root user in b2d, so not a huge issue there.
2015-06-09 15:11:49	<--	otter768 (~otter768@cpe-67-11-53-3.satx.res.rr.com) has quit (Ping timeout: 264 seconds)
2015-06-09 15:11:51	-->	micah_chatt (~micah_cha@ec2-54-84-43-177.compute-1.amazonaws.com) has joined #docker
