2015-06-10 09:13:15	philm88	Is it possible to have a docker container run docker-compose on the host system? I was hoping I could, from inside a container, do; ssh hostsystem <<<EOF cd /tmp/path; docker-compose up -d; EOF - but I get errors saying it cant connect to the Docker daemon
2015-06-10 09:13:34	<--	Freman (~twitsrus@2a00:1768:1004::1e7a:74e9) has quit (Ping timeout: 272 seconds)
2015-06-10 09:13:52	<--	pitiye (~pitiye@112.134.80.47) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-10 09:15:09	-->	otter768 (~otter768@cpe-67-11-53-3.satx.res.rr.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:15:50	philm88	Is SSH the wrong way to go?? Should I install docker-compose inside the container and have it use TLS to communicate with the docker daemon on the host instead?
2015-06-10 09:15:52	-->	Freman (~twitsrus@2a00:1768:1004::1e7a:74e9) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:16:01	San1ty	I am creating a docker image that executes a shell script as it's CMD and in that shell script I start a process in daemon mode. If I would run like this the container immediately quits because my shell script exits. Is there a way to not allow the container to stop without having to set up something like supervisord?
2015-06-10 09:16:04	<--	vikasyaligar (~vikasyali@116.202.172.67) has quit (Read error: Connection reset by peer)
2015-06-10 09:16:38	@programmerq	philm88: you can totally install docker-compose inside a container.
2015-06-10 09:16:43	ssalinas	San1ty: first thought is to not run the process in daemon mode
2015-06-10 09:16:50	-->	vikasyaligar (~vikasyali@116.202.172.67) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:17:00	@programmerq	you can do -v /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock
2015-06-10 09:17:15	@programmerq	that'll work in case you don't want to mess with TLS setup inside the container.
2015-06-10 09:17:22	San1ty	ssalinas: the problem is in not deamon mode it crashes complaning about terminal
2015-06-10 09:17:42	-->	Mic92 (~Mic92@login.higgsboson.tk) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:17:58	axl_	programmerq, might not work on mac XD
2015-06-10 09:18:06	philm88	programmerq: thanks, that sounds simple enough. Would TLS be the way to do it to have a container on hostA run docker-compose on hostB? Or can invoking it over ssh work?
2015-06-10 09:18:13	San1ty	ssalinas: I think I can get it to work with passing -t to the docker run command but I don't want to have to do that.
2015-06-10 09:18:15	@programmerq	axl_: who wouldn't that work on mac?
2015-06-10 09:18:19	<--	rock_theory (~brian@104.236.197.33) has quit (Quit: WeeChat 1.0.1)
2015-06-10 09:18:49	@programmerq	host volumes happen wherever the daemon runs, which is going to have docker.sock somewhere
2015-06-10 09:19:01	@programmerq	and that somewhere will be accessible with a host volume
2015-06-10 09:19:02	axl_	programmerq, sharing a sock
2015-06-10 09:19:09	-->	djx (~djx@av3-84-90-162-47.netvisao.pt) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:19:19	@programmerq	axl_: the socket isn't on the actual osx host though
2015-06-10 09:19:22	@programmerq	so it works
2015-06-10 09:19:24	<--	otter768 (~otter768@cpe-67-11-53-3.satx.res.rr.com) has quit (Ping timeout: 245 seconds)
2015-06-10 09:19:25	ssalinas	San1ty: then something like supervisord might be the way to go, otherwise you’ll have to write something that watches to be sure the daemon is running/properly handles signals/etc
2015-06-10 09:19:45	axl_	programmerq, oh ok
2015-06-10 09:19:45	San1ty	ssalinas: thank you very much I'll look into supervisord
2015-06-10 09:20:03	-->	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:20:04	@programmerq	host volumes happen on the docker host, not the VM host
2015-06-10 09:20:13	<--	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has quit (Max SendQ exceeded)
2015-06-10 09:20:43	-->	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:20:59	<--	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has quit (Max SendQ exceeded)
2015-06-10 09:21:31	-->	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:21:36	-->	cosql (~cosql@130.226.254.66) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:21:36	-->	pitiye (~pitiye@112.134.80.47) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:21:37	<--	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has quit (Max SendQ exceeded)
2015-06-10 09:22:10	-->	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:22:36	<--	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has quit (Max SendQ exceeded)
2015-06-10 09:22:39	axl_	programmerq, I tried for so long to share my ssh-agent sock, I failed on mac :/
2015-06-10 09:23:00	@programmerq	the ssh agent isn't running on the docker host
2015-06-10 09:23:10	-->	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:23:13	@programmerq	the docker daemon is on the docker host. :)
2015-06-10 09:23:18	<--	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has quit (Max SendQ exceeded)
2015-06-10 09:23:21	-->	micah_chatt (~micah_cha@ec2-54-84-43-177.compute-1.amazonaws.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:23:28	-->	azerus (~badass@unaffiliated/badass) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:23:29	<--	limpep (~ergunpola@90.216.134.198) has quit (Ping timeout: 252 seconds)
2015-06-10 09:23:49	@programmerq	but you are correct that sharing a socket doesn't work over virtualbox sharing, nor nfs, nor any other network filesystem really.
2015-06-10 09:23:53	-->	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:23:59	<--	errordeveloper (~ilya@94.118.8.3) has quit (Ping timeout: 245 seconds)
2015-06-10 09:24:01	@programmerq	not that I'm aware of, anyway.
2015-06-10 09:24:07	<--	pyo_ (~pyo@132.185.151.37) has quit
2015-06-10 09:24:11	<--	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has quit (Max SendQ exceeded)
2015-06-10 09:24:26	@programmerq	you could ssh -A into the VM running docker, and then share *taht* socket
2015-06-10 09:24:29	@programmerq	that*
2015-06-10 09:24:49	-->	Oxelist (~Oxelist@132.185.151.35) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 09:24:55	@programmerq	because the ssh server running on the VM is what actually holds that socket, and that's on the same host
