2015-06-10 12:08:06	-->	DoubleMalt (~DoubleMal@mx1.aurep.at) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 12:08:26	-->	Networkn3rd (~networkn3@12.23.74.29) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 12:08:39	<--	wallet42 (~wallet42@unaffiliated/wallet42) has quit (Quit: Leaving.)
2015-06-10 12:08:46	cpuguy83	detach-: Containers and VM's have some use-case overlap... but really two different beasts.
2015-06-10 12:08:54	detach-	cpuguy83: different technology I get it, different goals? not really. the guys who created VM also had the same idea that OSes (and applications) should run anywhere
2015-06-10 12:08:55	cpuguy83	detach-: Containers do not do virtualization in anyway.
2015-06-10 12:09:10	devster31	nope, new error Can't change to run as user 'mysql'
2015-06-10 12:09:45	<--	rossriley (~Adium@213.205.252.186) has quit (Client Quit)
2015-06-10 12:09:50	-->	wotak (~Thunderbi@ip54534ee8.adsl-surfen.hetnet.nl) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 12:09:52	cpuguy83	detach-: The goal of virtualization is abstracting the hardware. The goal of containers is abstracting all underlying infrastucture.
2015-06-10 12:09:59	detach-	cpuguy83: let's not talk about whether it's a hypervisor, or how it technically containerises stuff (that was what the old Sun Solaris "Zone" tried to do too, isn't that some sort of a VM too)
2015-06-10 12:10:14	<--	ssalinas (~ssalinas@63.139.127.4) has quit (Quit: ssalinas)
2015-06-10 12:10:27	<--	apschexn (~aps@97-84-199-97.dhcp.bycy.mi.charter.com) has quit (Quit: apschexn)
2015-06-10 12:10:31	detach-	cpuguy83: ok go on... how does it abstract the underlying infra
2015-06-10 12:10:33	cpuguy83	detach-: containers (at least docker ones) are about process isolation.
2015-06-10 12:10:36	detach-	cpuguy83: give me an example
2015-06-10 12:10:57	Skuggen	devster31: What platform are you running Docker on?
2015-06-10 12:11:05	detach-	cpuguy83: so are VMs, they are also used as a form of isolation
2015-06-10 12:11:14	devster31	ubuntu trusty 14.04 64bit
2015-06-10 12:11:31	cpuguy83	detach-: isolation at a completely different level
2015-06-10 12:11:40	detach-	cpuguy83: back in the old days people would run everything on a single server, e.g. a full LAMP stack, but with VMs the web/DB can be split into two VMs and isolated
2015-06-10 12:11:54	detach-	cpuguy83: i'm listening. maybe give me examples so I can understand better
2015-06-10 12:12:16	<--	shlant (~Adium@2602:306:32bf:d0b0:1184:bd52:5b14:cd91) has quit (Ping timeout: 256 seconds)
2015-06-10 12:12:25	<--	alunduil (~alunduil@gentoo/developer/alunduil) has quit (Ping timeout: 264 seconds)
2015-06-10 12:12:31	-->	donspaulding (~donspauld@107.152.3.83) has joined #docker
2015-06-10 12:13:10	cpuguy83	detach-: Ok fire up an EC2 instances with your apps. Ok now move them to Azure.
2015-06-10 12:14:04	detach-	cpuguy83: That's like telling me to move from an AMD server to an Intel server whilst running VMware. I don't have that problem.
2015-06-10 12:14:05	cpuguy83	dtzWill: Now do the same thing, but instead run the apps in docker on each.
2015-06-10 12:14:36	cpuguy83	detach-: I'm making a point
2015-06-10 12:14:40	<--	nemothekid (~textual@c-67-164-73-212.hsd1.ca.comcast.net) has quit (Quit: My MacBook has gone to sleep. ZZZzzz…)
2015-06-10 12:14:43	detach-	cpuguy83: OK more examples?
2015-06-10 12:15:09	cpuguy83	VM's _can_ be used for app isolation, but at a hefty cost
2015-06-10 12:15:24	cpuguy83	But that's not the point of the VM
2015-06-10 12:15:37	<--	christyp (~christyp@32.97.110.51) has quit (Ping timeout: 258 seconds)
2015-06-10 12:15:42	cpuguy83	Containers are specifically for app isolation
2015-06-10 12:16:26	<--	milka (~milka@unaffiliated/milka) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-10 12:16:36	cpuguy83	And Docker is specifically for enabling better flow from dev->test->staging->prod
2015-06-10 12:16:38	<--	DoubleMalt (~DoubleMal@mx1.aurep.at) has quit (Ping timeout: 265 seconds)
2015-06-10 12:16:41	detach-	So can I run my docker app in Linux, Windows, MacOS?
