2015-06-12 12:51:08	<--	p4trix (~p4trix@232.Red-79-145-254.dynamicIP.rima-tde.net) has quit (Quit: Leaving)
2015-06-12 12:52:12	-->	lynchc (~lynch@50.242.98.66) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:52:37	<--	Xethron (~Xethron@unaffiliated/xethron) has quit (Ping timeout: 264 seconds)
2015-06-12 12:52:53	--	smathy_afk is now known as smathy
2015-06-12 12:53:05	foist	Has anyone found a way to efficiently manage dependencies with Docker? If I change a single line of my requirements.txt file, the cache is invalidated and I have to build all the requirements again.
2015-06-12 12:53:30	<--	nemothekid (~textual@c-67-164-73-212.hsd1.ca.comcast.net) has quit (Quit: My MacBook has gone to sleep. ZZZzzz…)
2015-06-12 12:53:31	foist	It doesn’t look like I’m alone in this: https://muffinresearch.co.uk/docker-and-dependencies/
2015-06-12 12:53:35	-->	simplyianm (~simplyian@75-101-56-74.dsl.static.fusionbroadband.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:54:58	<--	Goopyo (~Goopyo@ec2-54-173-68-6.compute-1.amazonaws.com) has quit (Quit: Goopyo)
2015-06-12 12:55:02	-->	arunpyasi (~arunpyasi@45.64.161.52) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:55:12	zalmoxes	foist: you need to first copy requirements.txt at the top of your dockerfile
2015-06-12 12:55:16	zalmoxes	that caches it
2015-06-12 12:55:20	kolbe	at the top?
2015-06-12 12:55:27	<--	Savemech (Savemech@gateway/shell/bnc4free/x-utoaggkdznqbevnd) has quit (Quit: I'm using a Free IRC Bouncer from BNC4FREE - http://bnc4free.com/)
2015-06-12 12:55:31	foist	That’s even worse.
2015-06-12 12:55:41	kolbe	i think he's saying that if he changes it outside of the Docker environment, a new build will cause all following layers to be re-done
2015-06-12 12:55:43	<--	tommmied (~tomdevito@static-173-63-73-14.nwrknj.fios.verizon.net) has quit (Quit: tommmied)
2015-06-12 12:55:47	<--	arunpyasi (~arunpyasi@45.64.161.52) has quit (Max SendQ exceeded)
2015-06-12 12:56:01	<--	jeffme (~jeffme@12.130.117.155) has quit (Quit: My Mac has gone to sleep. ZZZzzz…)
2015-06-12 12:56:19	-->	arunpyasi (~arunpyasi@45.64.161.52) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:56:19	kolbe	foist: Docker can't really know what effect a changed requirements.txt file will have on later layers, so it has to re-build all layers that come after the changed resource. if requirements.txt doesn't affect some layers, define those layers *before* requirements.txt in the Dockerfile
2015-06-12 12:56:31	-->	bigl0af (~smuxi@216.240.30.5) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:56:55	-->	rsampaio_ (~rodrigo@152.179.69.246) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:57:22	zalmoxes	yes, but if you install your requirements first, unless requirements.txt changes, pip is not gonna run each time
2015-06-12 12:57:23	-->	slamp (~Thunderbi@ANice-651-1-293-225.w83-201.abo.wanadoo.fr) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:57:27	foist	The problem is that requirements.txt defines some number of dependancies, most of which rarely change. If I update the version number on a single one fo them, the entire set of dependencies has to be re-downloaded and re-built.
2015-06-12 12:57:31	<--	pengin (~pengin@38.104.129.98) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-12 12:57:34	-->	Savemech (Savemech@gateway/shell/bnc4free/x-titnqcxayybsyavv) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:57:51	kolbe	foist: right, there's simply no way for Docker to know how those dependencies interact with one another or what effect any of this might have
2015-06-12 12:58:18	zalmoxes	foist: look at this https://github.com/groob/docker-munkiwebadmin/blob/alpine/Dockerfile
2015-06-12 12:58:21	foist	I’m considering installing each dependency on its own line in the Dockerfile with a `RUN pip install foo==1.3`.
2015-06-12 12:58:24	zalmoxes	i copy first to /tmp and run install
2015-06-12 12:58:33	zalmoxes	that caches my dependencies
2015-06-12 12:58:43	-->	Goopyo (~Goopyo@ec2-54-173-68-6.compute-1.amazonaws.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 12:58:51	foist	zalmoxes: and what happens if you update a single line in requirements.txt?
2015-06-12 12:59:12	zalmoxes	well then you have to rebuild your dependencies
2015-06-12 12:59:21	<--	renlo (~renlo@67.207.106.11) has quit (Quit: renlo)
2015-06-12 12:59:22	zalmoxes	but you dont update your dependencies as often as everything else
2015-06-12 12:59:26	kolbe	foist: i've never used this requirements.txt thing, so i don't know anything about it specifically. but even if you put each thing on its own RUN line, a change to one of *those* lines will require you to re-build later layers..
2015-06-12 12:59:44	foist	zalmoxes: which is the problem I’m describing.
2015-06-12 12:59:59	zalmoxes	how often do you update your python project's dependencies ?
2015-06-12 13:00:03	<--	drmabuse (~drmabuse@HSI-KBW-078-042-203-126.hsi3.kabel-badenwuerttemberg.de) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-12 13:00:05	-->	renlo (~renlo@67.207.106.11) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:00:25	kolbe	foist: there is no good way around this, as far as i know. Docker's knowledge of the interplay between various dependencies is basically non-existent (again afaik)
2015-06-12 13:00:31	<--	bturker_ (~bturker@76.74.153.41) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-12 13:00:34	owen1	when i run nginx in a container, i point an 'upstream' to another container by putting the docker-0 ip into my nginx config. how does it know to go to the right place?
2015-06-12 13:00:37	foist	kolbe: True. But the most common change to requirements.txt is an addition. If I append new requirements to the end of the list, it may avoid a large portion of cases.
2015-06-12 13:00:44	-->	paul_andrew (~user@h36n2.telgenat.ias.bredband.telia.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:01:07	kolbe	foist: aha, if you're just adding new things, then i'd do away with requirements.txt and put things in the Dockerfile directly
2015-06-12 13:01:22	foist	zalmoxes: often enough that downloading all the deps for remote workers in regions with a poor connection is a problem.
2015-06-12 13:01:23	<--	simplyianm (~simplyian@75-101-56-74.dsl.static.fusionbroadband.com) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-12 13:01:59	kolbe	foist: a pretty standard workflow is to use lots of RUN commands while developing your image, and then when you're comfortable with its behavior, you combine those into a single RUN command that does a lot of operations and cleans up after them. that reduces the number of layers and gets rid of crusty files you don't need
2015-06-12 13:02:04	zalmoxes	you can set up a cache for the remote workers so they install dependencies from a local source
2015-06-12 13:02:24	foist	zalmoxes: how does that work?
2015-06-12 13:02:49	zalmoxes	foist http://stackoverflow.com/questions/4806448/how-do-i-install-from-a-local-cache-with-pip
2015-06-12 13:02:58	foist	kolbe: how do you combine RUN commands? Just RUN foo && bar && etc?
2015-06-12 13:03:06	zalmoxes	i am not a python developer but i'm sure you can set up a local pip cache
2015-06-12 13:03:21	zalmoxes	foist: yes
2015-06-12 13:03:44	zalmoxes	if you look at the dockerfile I sent you, that's about as efficient you're going to get with RUN commands
2015-06-12 13:04:09	foist	But combining them would defeat the purpose...
2015-06-12 13:04:21	-->	mrmargolis (~mrmargoli@h69-128-47-52.mdsnwi.dedicated.static.tds.net) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:04:23	<--	tiagoboldt (~tiagobold@193.137.28.184) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-12 13:04:24	kolbe	foist: yep
2015-06-12 13:04:37	zalmoxes	it depends what your purpose is
2015-06-12 13:04:39	kolbe	foist: right, i'm saying that you combine them as the last step before you build your image for distribution
2015-06-12 13:04:42	zalmoxes	combining layers makes your image smaller
2015-06-12 13:05:01	foist	kolbe: I don’t distribute an image. I have devs build the image from the Dockerfile.
2015-06-12 13:05:03	-->	tiagoboldt (~tiagobold@193.137.28.184) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:05:08	kolbe	foist: i just explained that *during development* you have a lot of separate RUN commands, but that makes a bloated image with a lot of layers. so, after you are done developing the image, combine them togther before you distribute the image.
2015-06-12 13:05:15	zalmoxes	foist: why?
2015-06-12 13:05:16	kolbe	foist: well devs aren't going to like some shitty bloated image, either
2015-06-12 13:05:48	zalmoxes	push an image to a registry, have devs docker pull
2015-06-12 13:05:54	<--	Hugodby (~Hugodby@2607:fad8:4:6:884a:66b:5ccc:9aca) has quit (Ping timeout: 256 seconds)
2015-06-12 13:06:00	-->	digen (~digen@unaffiliated/digen) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:06:16	foist	zalmoxes: I see no point in introducing a new remote service I have to pay for. God knows Github alone goes down often enough.
2015-06-12 13:06:55	kolbe	i think it's fine for your devs to build their own images
2015-06-12 13:06:56	foist	Though I’m only using Docker for development right now. When I add it to my CI and start deploying with it, I’ll probably start using the Docker Hub.
2015-06-12 13:07:31	-->	jonlangemak (~Jon@64-83-229-82.static.stcd.mn.charter.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:07:31	-->	cosql (~cosql@130.226.254.66) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:07:53	zalmoxes	the docker registry could be hosted by you.. a digitalocean instance is 5/mo for a private registry
2015-06-12 13:07:56	<--	digen (~digen@unaffiliated/digen) has quit (Client Quit)
2015-06-12 13:08:30	-->	trkemist (~trkemist@unaffiliated/trkemist) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:08:53	zalmoxes	foist: how do you host your vagrant images
2015-06-12 13:09:05	foist	Don’t use Vagrant.
2015-06-12 13:09:20	zalmoxes	:/
2015-06-12 13:09:48	<--	nathanleclaire (~nathanlec@c-73-189-234-64.hsd1.ca.comcast.net) has quit (Quit: nathanleclaire)
2015-06-12 13:09:53	foist	Yes?
2015-06-12 13:09:55	-->	bmurphy1976 (~bmurphy19@ec2-107-23-156-96.compute-1.amazonaws.com) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:10:04	trkemist	Hey I have a question fro the group. Does anyone know where I can get a writeup on how to install older versions of docker?
2015-06-12 13:10:10	<--	doniphon_ (~doniphon@foresight/developer/doniphon) has quit (Ping timeout: 244 seconds)
2015-06-12 13:10:35	<--	mewm (~textual@94.126.177.1) has quit (Quit: Textual IRC Client: www.textualapp.com)
2015-06-12 13:12:01	foist	zalmoxes: is there more of a comment to the emoticon of disapproval?
2015-06-12 13:13:35	kolbe	foist: i think if your goal is to reduce the chaos and flailing of building more layers than you want, your only option is to put a lot of RUN statements in Dockerfile. the takeaway for you is that this creates larger and less efficient images, but perhaps you don't care about that because it's just for dev and not for distribution.
2015-06-12 13:13:56	<--	mramm (~mramm@2602:306:3097:2a0:d88a:3d67:c171:5249) has quit (Remote host closed the connection)
2015-06-12 13:14:01	kolbe	foist: if you eventually begin distributing docker images, you will want to re-visit the subject of combining multiple RUN directives in order to reduce image size and improve efficiency. EOF
2015-06-12 13:14:15	<--	lynchc (~lynch@50.242.98.66) has quit (Ping timeout: 250 seconds)
2015-06-12 13:14:15	foist	kolbe: what do you mean by less efficient? What are the perceivable affects of being “less efficient"
2015-06-12 13:14:35	-->	mramm (~mramm@2602:306:3097:2a0:d88a:3d67:c171:5249) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:14:40	-->	lynchc (~lynch@50.242.98.66) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:15:03	kolbe	foist: more and more layers means more and more crap for docker/kernel/filesystem to deal with, which can probably make performance suffer a bit
2015-06-12 13:15:07	-->	bturker (~bturker@17.199.70.78) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:15:22	-->	mikedougherty (~mikedough@199-83-220-202.PUBLIC.monkeybrains.net) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:16:02	-->	f2s (~dmccue@cpc1-bele9-2-0-cust131.2-1.cable.virginm.net) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:16:41	kolbe	foist: there are a lot of blog posts and other information about this; you might have better luck trying to read through some of those
2015-06-12 13:16:47	-->	plucas (~plucas@8.18.218.175) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:17:13	kolbe	foist: http://www.extellisys.com/articles/docker-layer-overload for example (though i haven't read this in detail and thus don't vouch for this article specifically)
2015-06-12 13:17:19	-->	solidnerd (~Niclas@5.147.10.8) has joined #docker
2015-06-12 13:18:02	foist	Thanks kolbe. I’ll revisit the subject at some point.
